e_list.dart`\n5. Check if there are any issues with the `send-message.dto.ts` - 
specifically, `content` is optional when type is "image" but required when type 
is "text". However, in `im.service.ts`, it checks `dto.type === "image" && !dto.
content` which would throw if content is missing for image. But the DTO doesn\'t
enforce `content` for image messages at all - `@ValidateIf((o) => o.type === "te
xt")` means `content` is only validated when type is text. So for image messages
, `content` could be completely missing (undefined), and the Service check `!dto
.content` would catch it. That\'s fine.\n\nWait, but what about `type: "system"`
? The DTO allows `system` in `@IsIn(["text", "image", "system"])`. But the Servi
ce doesn\'t handle `system` type in `sendMessage` - it only has checks for `text
` and `image`. A `system` message sent via the API would pass DTO validation (si
nce content is optional when type != text) and pass the service checks (since it
\'s not text or image). Then it would try to save with `content: undefined`. But
the entity says `content: string` (not nullable). Actually wait, `content` colum
n is `@Column("text")` without `nullable: true`, so it defaults to NOT NULL. Sav
ing with undefined might cause a DB error or save empty string depending on Type
ORM.\n\nBut system messages should only be created internally by the server, not
sent by users via the API. The API allows it though. This could be a security is
sue - users could send fake system messages. But the PRD says "打开会话时，若数
据库中无系统消息记录，后端自动插入一条 type = \'system\' 的消息作为欢迎语." It d
oesn\'t say users can send system messages.\n\nThis is a Major issue: `send-mess
age.dto.ts` allows `type: "system"` which users should not be able to send.\n\nL
et me check the API contract file.',
    encrypted=None
)
